title: For Sale:  1941 Tula SVT-40
postcontent:
\\\\SOLD; PENDING DEACTIVATION

The rifle up for sale is a 1941 Tula SVT-40 in very good condition. Finish on the rifle is as to be expected; shows some wear, minor chips to the shellac finish, and a small section of wood behind the trigger guard was replaced during re-arsenaling post war.

The bore is in good shape, especially given the typical pitting and rough nature one usually finds an SVT-40 bore in. The lands are bright and shinny, while the bore is a little dark and has some frost to it. The rifle is accurate, producing groups of 4-6 MOA with cheap ammo and surplus, and will shoot ~2 MOA with match and high quality surplus such as Yugo, and the recent import of 60's Russian Match ammo.

The stock matches the rifles, but the magazine is a parts bin mismatch. Rifle functions flawlessly with everything accept lacquer and polymer coated ammunition. The action makes use of a fluted chamber, which blows gas back around the case, to keep the case from sticking. While this works great for brass and steel, it has the opposite effect on lacquer/polymer, causing it to melt the coating. Not the fault of the rifle, just a bugbear of the design. Also, I would not feed this rifle any brass you want to keep, as the charging handle functions as a brass deflector and WILL bend your cases.

I am willing to meet face-to-face anywhere in Pensacola, and will entertain any reasonable offer. I am also willing to ship outside the Pensacola area, but will wait until payment clears before shipping the rifle to your FFL of choice. I have an FFL who will act as a shipping agent.

I apologize in advance for the lack of photos as I don't have a camera capable of taking a decent quality picture.

title: For Sale:  1941 Tula SVT-40
postcontent:
The rifle up for sale is a 1941 Tula SVT-40 in very good condition. Finish on the rifle is as to be expected; shows some wear, minor chips to the shellac finish, and a small section of wood behind the trigger guard was replaced during re-arsenaling post war.

The bore is in good shape, especially given the typical pitting and rough nature one usually finds an SVT-40 bore in. The lands are bright and shinny, while the bore is a little dark and has some frost to it. The rifle is accurate, producing groups of 4-6 MOA with cheap ammo and surplus, and will shoot ~2 MOA with match and high quality surplus such as Yugo, and the recent import of 60's Russian Match ammo.

The stock matches the rifles, but the magazine is a parts bin mismatch. Rifle functions flawlessly with everything accept lacquer and polymer coated ammunition. The action makes use of a fluted chamber, which blows gas back around the case, to keep the case from sticking. While this works great for brass and steel, it has the opposite effect on lacquer/polymer, causing it to melt the coating. Not the fault of the rifle, just a bugbear of the design. Also, I would not feed this rifle any brass you want to keep, as the charging handle functions as a brass deflector and WILL bend your cases.

I am willing to meet face-to-face anywhere in Pensacola, and will entertain any reasonable offer. I am also willing to ship outside the Pensacola area, but will wait until payment clears before shipping the rifle to your FFL of choice. I have an FFL who will act as a shipping agent.

I apologize in advance for the lack of photos as I don't have a camera capable of taking a decent quality picture.
